<p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_49-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-h=
tml mntl-sc-block-html"> An analyst would interpret this output to mean tha=
t if other variables are held constant, the price of XOM will increase by 7=
.8% if the price of oil in the markets increases by 1%.
</p>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_50-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_51-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-h=
tml mntl-sc-block-html"> The model also shows that the price of XOM will de=
crease by 1.5% following a 1% rise in interest rates. R<sup>2</sup> indicat=
es that 86.5% of the variations in the stock price of Exxon Mobil can be ex=
plained by changes in the interest rate, oil price, oil futures, and S&amp;=
P 500 index.
</p>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_52-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<span class=3D"heading-toc" id=3D"toc-linear-vs-multiple-regression"></span=
><h2 id=3D"mntl-sc-block_53-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block=
-heading mntl-sc-block-heading"> <span class=3D"mntl-sc-block-heading__text=
 text-title-300"> Linear vs. Multiple Regression </span> </h2>
<p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_54-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-h=
tml mntl-sc-block-html"> <a href=3D"https://www.investopedia.com/terms/l/le=
ast-squares-method.asp" data-component=3D"link" data-source=3D"inlineLink" =
data-type=3D"internalLink" data-ordinal=3D"1">Ordinary linear squares</a> (=
OLS) regression compares the response of a dependent variable given a chang=
e in some explanatory variables. However, a dependent variable is rarely ex=
plained by only one variable. In this case, an analyst uses multiple regres=
sion, which attempts to explain a dependent variable using more than one in=
dependent variable.
</p>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_55-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_56-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-h=
tml mntl-sc-block-html"> Multiple regressions can be linear and nonlinear. =
MLRs are based on the assumption that there is a linear relationship betwee=
n both the dependent and independent variables. It also assumes no major co=
rrelation between the independent variables.
</p>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_57-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<span class=3D"heading-toc" id=3D"toc-explain-like-im-5"></span><h2 id=3D"m=
ntl-sc-block_58-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-heading mnt=
l-sc-block-heading"> <span class=3D"mntl-sc-block-heading__text text-title-=
300"> Explain Like I'm 5 </span> </h2>
<p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_59-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-h=
tml mntl-sc-block-html"> Multiple linear regression is used to determine ho=
w different factors affect something you want to predict. For example, you'=
re trying to figure out how much an oil stock will be priced at.
</p>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_60-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_61-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-h=
tml mntl-sc-block-html"> Rather than looking at just one factor, like the o=
verall market, MLR considers many factors at once, like oil prices, interes=
t rates, and the market index, to make a better prediction. Each of these f=
actors has its own influence on the stock price, and MLR helps calculate ho=
w much each one matters.
</p>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_62-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_63-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-h=
tml mntl-sc-block-html"> The MLR model assumes that the relationship betwee=
n the outcome (the stock's price) and the factors is linear and that the fa=
ctors are not highly correlated with one another. The result gives you a cl=
earer picture of what is really driving the changes and how strong each fac=
tor's impact is. MLR is used in finance, economics, and other fields to und=
erstand relationships and make predictions.<br>
</p>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_64-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_65-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block=
-questionandanswer mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer"><span class=3D"heading-=
toc" id=3D"toc-what-makes-a-multiple-regression-multiple"></span> <h2 class=
=3D"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__question">What Makes a Multiple Regres=
sion Multiple?</h2>
<div class=3D"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__answer"><p>Multiple regressi=
on considers the effect of more than one explanatory variable on some outco=
me of interest. It evaluates the relative effect of these explanatory, or i=
ndependent, variables on the dependent variable when holding all the other =
variables in the model constant.</p></div>
</div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_66-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_67-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block=
-questionandanswer mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer"><span class=3D"heading-=
toc" id=3D"toc-why-would-one-use-a-multiple-regression-over-a-simple-ols-re=
gression"></span> <h2 class=3D"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__question">W=
hy Would One Use a Multiple Regression Over a Simple OLS Regression?</h2>
<div class=3D"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__answer"><p>A dependent varia=
ble is rarely explained by only one variable. In such cases, an analyst use=
s multiple regression, which attempts to explain a dependent variable using=
 more than one independent variable. The model, however, assumes that there=
 are no major correlations between the independent variables.</p></div>
</div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_68-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_69-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block=
-questionandanswer mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer"><span class=3D"heading-=
toc" id=3D"toc-can-i-do-a-multiple-regression-by-hand"></span> <h2 class=3D=
"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__question">Can I Do a Multiple Regression =
by Hand?</h2>
<div class=3D"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__answer"><p>It's unlikely as =
multiple regression models are complex and become even more so when there a=
re more variables included in the model or when the amount of data to analy=
ze grows. To run a multiple regression, you will likely need to use special=
ized statistical software or functions within programs like Excel.</p></div=
>
</div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_70-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_71-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block=
-questionandanswer mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer"><span class=3D"heading-=
toc" id=3D"toc-what-does-it-mean-for-a-multiple-regression-to-be-linear"></=
span> <h2 class=3D"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__question">What Does It =
Mean for a Multiple Regression to Be Linear?</h2>
<div class=3D"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__answer"><p>In multiple linea=
r regression, the model calculates the <a href=3D"https://www.investopedia.=
com/terms/l/line-of-best-fit.asp" data-component=3D"link" data-source=3D"in=
lineLink" data-type=3D"internalLink" data-ordinal=3D"1">line of best fit</a=
> that minimizes the variances of each of the variables included as it rela=
tes to the dependent variable. Because it fits a line, it is a linear model=
. There are also non-linear regression models involving multiple variables,=
 such as logistic regression, quadratic regression, and probit models.</p><=
/div>
</div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_72-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_73-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block=
-questionandanswer mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer"><span class=3D"heading-=
toc" id=3D"toc-how-are-multiple-regression-models-used-in-finance"></span> =
<h2 class=3D"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__question">How Are Multiple Re=
gression Models Used in Finance?</h2>
<div class=3D"mntl-sc-block-questionandanswer__answer"><p>Any econometric m=
odel that looks at more than one variable may be a multiple. <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/multifactor-model.asp" data-component=3D"=
link" data-source=3D"inlineLink" data-type=3D"internalLink" data-ordinal=3D=
"1">Factor models</a> compare two or more factors to analyze relationships =
between variables and the resulting performance.</p><p>The <a href=3D"https=
://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/famaandfrenchthreefactormodel.asp" data-com=
ponent=3D"link" data-source=3D"inlineLink" data-type=3D"internalLink" data-=
ordinal=3D"2">Fama and French Three-Factor Mod</a> is a model that expands =
on the <a href=3D"https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/capm.asp" data-compo=
nent=3D"link" data-source=3D"inlineLink" data-type=3D"internalLink" data-or=
dinal=3D"3">capital asset pricing model</a> (CAPM) by adding size risk and =
value risk factors to the market risk factor in CAPM (which is itself a reg=
ression model). By including these two additional factors, the model adjust=
s for this outperforming tendency, which is thought to make it a better too=
l for evaluating manager performance.</p></div>
</div>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_74-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<span class=3D"heading-toc" id=3D"toc-the-bottom-line"></span><h2 id=3D"mnt=
l-sc-block_75-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-heading mntl-=
sc-block-heading"> <span class=3D"mntl-sc-block-heading__text text-title-30=
0"> The Bottom Line </span> </h2>
<p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_76-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-h=
tml mntl-sc-block-html"> MLR is a statistical tool used to predict the outc=
ome of a variable based on two or more explanatory variables. If just one v=
ariable affects the dependent variable, a simple linear regression model is=
 sufficient. If, on the other hand, more than one thing affects that variab=
le, MLR is needed.
</p>
<div id=3D"mntl-sc-block_77-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-ad=
slot mntl-block"></div>
<p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_78-0" class=3D"comp mntl-sc-block finance-sc-block-h=
tml mntl-sc-block-html"> A classic example would be the drivers of a compan=
y=E2=80=99s valuation on the stock market. Usually, a company=E2=80=99s sha=
re price is influenced by a variety of factors. In this case, the dependent=
 variable would be the share price, which is the thing we are trying to pre=
dict, while the independent, explanatory variables would be the factors tha=
t affect it.
</p></div>
